                        "steps":  [
                                      "Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. While it heats, trim the tough lower stems from the broccoli rabe and cut the bunch into large pieces.",
                                      "Add the orecchiette to the boiling water and cook until just shy of al dente. Before removing the pasta, reserve at least 1 cup of starchy pasta water for the sauce.",
                                      "Use a spider, slotted spoon, or strainer to scoop the pasta out of the pot and set it aside. Keep the water boiling, then add the broccoli rabe and blanch for 2 to 3 minutes, until the stems are just tender and the greens look bright.",
                                      "Drain the broccoli rabe, let it cool slightly, then roughly chop it into bite-size pieces. If using broccoli instead, skip the blanching and air fry florets with a little oil and salt until browned and tender.",
                                      "While the pasta and broccoli rabe cook, heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add the sausage and cook for 6 to 8 minutes, breaking it into small pieces, until browned and cooked through.",
                                      "Move the sausage to a plate, leaving the browned pork fond and a little fat in the skillet. Lower the heat to medium and add the butter and sliced shallots.",
                                      "Cook the shallots for 4 to 6 minutes, stirring often, until softened, lightly golden, and starting to caramelize in the sausage drippings. Add the garlic and red pepper flakes if using, and stir for 30 to 60 seconds until fragrant.",
                                      "Add about 1/2 cup reserved pasta water to the skillet and scrape up the browned bits from the bottom. Simmer for 1 to 2 minutes, until the shallots look glossy and the liquid starts to pull together into a light sauce.",
                                      "Return the sausage to the skillet, then add the chopped broccoli rabe and orecchiette. Toss over medium heat for 1 to 2 minutes, adding more pasta water a splash at a time if the pan looks dry.",
                                      "Add the grated Parmesan or Pecorino and toss again until the pasta looks glossy and lightly coated. Taste and adjust with black pepper, more cheese, or a small splash of chicken broth only if the sauce needs more volume."
                                  ],
